; It's fairly common in OCaml projects for the executable to simply surface entry-points
; in the project's libraries. This is done to maximize code composability and reusability.
; So, every DayN .exe here just tends to run its counterpart in Aoc2025.DayN.cmd

(executables
 (public_names main)
 ; promote until-clean populates the compiled .exe into the source directory.
 ; I do this so I don't have to remember where it's created in _build, and also
 ; so I don't have to do `dune exec ./day1.exe` to run. just `./day1.exe`
 (promote (until-clean))
 (names main)
 (libraries aoc2025 core_unix.command_unix))
